@node Session management
@section Session management

@findex wikipedia-login
The command @code{wikipedia-login} establishes a session with a wiki site. @*
When called interactively, it prompts for a site name from those @*
configured in @code{mediawiki-site-alist}.  You must call this command (or @*
let it be called implicitly) before using any other @samp{wikipedia.el} @*
commands.  Most commands call @code{wp--ensure-logged-in} internally, which @*
will prompt you to select a site if no session is active. @*

@node Page editing
@section Page editing

@findex wikipedia-open
@findex wikipedia-publish
@findex wikipedia-browse
The command @code{wikipedia-open} opens a Wikipedia page for editing in a @*
@samp{mediawiki-mode} buffer.  When called interactively, it prompts for the @*
page title, defaulting to the title at point if available (for example, @*
when invoked from a watchlist or history buffer). @*

The command @code{wikipedia-publish} saves the current buffer's content back @*
to the wiki.  It accepts an optional edit summary; when called @*
interactively, @samp{mediawiki.el} prompts for one if needed.  The alias @*
@code{wikipedia-save} is provided for discoverability. @*

The command @code{wikipedia-browse} opens the page in an external web browser @*
via @code{browse-url}.  Like @code{wikipedia-open}, it defaults to the title at @*
point. @*

@findex wikipedia-edit-mode
The minor mode @code{wikipedia-edit-mode} provides additional keybindings when @*
editing a wiki page.  It displays @samp{WP} in the mode line lighter and @*
binds @samp{C-c C-p} to @code{wikipedia-preview}. @*

@node Preview
@section Preview

@findex wikipedia-preview
@findex wikipedia-preview-edit
@findex wikipedia-preview-refresh
The command @code{wikipedia-preview} sends the current buffer's wikitext to @*
the MediaWiki parse API and displays the rendered HTML in a dedicated @*
preview buffer.  The preview uses @code{shr-render-region} to display the @*
HTML as formatted text within Emacs. @*

The preview buffer uses @code{wikipedia-preview-mode}, which provides the @*
following keybindings: @*

@multitable {aaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa}
@headitem Key
@tab Command
@tab Description
@item @samp{e}
@tab @code{wikipedia-preview-edit}
@tab Switch back to the source buffer
@item @samp{g}
@tab @code{wikipedia-preview-refresh}
@tab Re-render the preview from source
@item @samp{q}
@tab @code{quit-window}
@tab Close the preview window
@end multitable

The preview buffer supports @code{revert-buffer} (bound to @samp{g} in @*
@code{special-mode}), which re-fetches the preview from the source buffer. @*

@node Draft management
@section Draft management

@findex wikipedia-draft-save
@findex wikipedia-draft-open
@findex wikipedia-draft-delete
Drafts allow you to save work-in-progress edits locally before @*
publishing them to the wiki.  Each draft is a @samp{.wiki} file stored in @*
@code{wikipedia-draft-directory} (@ref{Draft storage}). @*

The command @code{wikipedia-draft-save} saves the current buffer's content as @*
a local draft.  It requires the buffer to have a page title set (as is @*
the case when editing a page opened via @code{wikipedia-open}).  Saving a @*
draft for the same page overwrites the previous draft. @*

The command @code{wikipedia-draft-open} prompts you to select a draft from @*
the list of saved drafts, then opens it in a @samp{mediawiki-mode} buffer @*
with @code{wikipedia-edit-mode} enabled.  From there, you can continue @*
editing and eventually publish with @code{wikipedia-publish}. @*

The command @code{wikipedia-draft-delete} prompts for a draft to delete, with @*
a confirmation prompt before removing the file. @*

Page titles are encoded into safe filenames using a byte-level escape @*
scheme: characters outside @samp{[a-zA-Z0-9 .-]} are replaced with @samp{_XX} @*
sequences (where @samp{XX} is the hexadecimal byte value of each UTF-8 @*
byte).  This ensures filenames are portable across operating systems @*
while remaining mostly human-readable for ASCII titles. @*

@node Watchlist
@section Watchlist

@findex wikipedia-watchlist
@findex wikipedia-watchlist-refresh
The command @code{wikipedia-watchlist} opens a buffer displaying your @*
Wikipedia watchlist.  Entries are grouped by page title: each page @*
appears as a collapsible group header showing the most recent change @*
summary, the contributing users, and the total size change.  A @samp{#} @*
column shows the number of changes when a page has more than one. @*

The watchlist fetches all unseen changes from the last 30 days, @*
including bot and minor edits.  This ensures that reverts are included @*
in the group, so that group diffs accurately reflect the net change. @*
After loading, it asynchronously prefetches revision content in the @*
background so that diffs can be displayed instantly when you navigate @*
to an entry. @*

When the @samp{gptel} package is installed, the watchlist supports AI @*
review scoring (@ref{AI review}).  A @samp{Score} column shows the @*
priority score (0.0--1.0) for each page.  Scores are persisted in the @*
local database and restored automatically when the watchlist is @*
reopened. @*

