@node XTools statistics
@section XTools statistics

The XTools commands fetch and display editing statistics from the @*
@uref{https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/XTools/API, XTools API}, a service that provides detailed analysis of editing @*
activity on MediaWiki projects.  These commands supplement the @*
information available through the MediaWiki API with data such as top @*
edited pages and detailed edit breakdowns. @*

@menu
* User statistics::
* Page statistics::
@end menu

@node User statistics
@subsection User statistics

@findex wikipedia-xtools-user-stats
The command @code{wikipedia-xtools-user-stats} displays comprehensive @*
statistics for a user.  The output includes: @*

@itemize
@item
Basic information: user ID, registration date, project. @*
@item
Admin status (highlighted if the user is a sysop or bureaucrat). @*
@item
Edit counts: live edits, deleted edits, total, and pages created. @*
@item
Activity period: first edit and most recent edit timestamps. @*
@item
User group memberships (local and global). @*
@item
Top 10 most-edited pages in the article namespace. @*
@end itemize

The command combines data from both the XTools API (edit counts) and the @*
MediaWiki API (registration, groups, contribution timestamps) to present @*
a unified view. @*

@node Page statistics
@subsection Page statistics

@findex wikipedia-xtools-page-stats
@findex wikipedia-xtools-top-editors
The command @code{wikipedia-xtools-page-stats} displays statistics for a @*
page, including revision count, number of editors, minor edit count, @*
average edit size, page size, creation date, and top editors. @*

The command @code{wikipedia-xtools-top-editors} displays a detailed list of @*
the top editors for a page, showing each editor's edit count, minor edit @*
count, and the date range of their activity. @*

@node Synchronization and local mirror
@section Synchronization and local mirror

The synchronization and mirror system stores Wikipedia pages and their @*
revision history in a local SQLite database, enabling offline browsing @*
and faster access to frequently visited pages. @*

@menu
* Synchronizing pages::
* Browsing the local mirror::
* Local revision history::
* Database management::
@end menu

@node Synchronizing pages
@subsection Synchronizing pages

@findex wikipedia-sync-page
@findex wikipedia-sync-watchlist
@findex wikipedia-sync-update
The command @code{wikipedia-sync-page} synchronizes a single page to the @*
local database.  It downloads revision metadata (up to @*
@code{wikipedia-sync-revision-limit} revisions) and, if @*
@code{wikipedia-sync-fetch-content} is non-nil, the full wikitext of the most @*
recent revision. @*

The command @code{wikipedia-sync-watchlist} performs a bulk synchronization of @*
all pages from your watchlist.  It first fetches the watchlist, marks @*
each page as watched in the database, and then synchronizes each page @*
individually with a brief delay between requests to avoid overloading @*
the server.  Pages that fail to synchronize are reported in a summary @*
message without aborting the remaining pages. @*

The command @code{wikipedia-sync-update} re-synchronizes all pages already @*
marked as watched in the local database.  Use this for routine updates @*
after the initial @code{wikipedia-sync-watchlist} import. @*

@node Browsing the local mirror
@subsection Browsing the local mirror

@findex wikipedia-mirror
@findex wikipedia-mirror-refresh
@findex wikipedia-mirror-open-page
@findex wikipedia-mirror-show-history
@findex wikipedia-mirror-sync-page
@findex wikipedia-mirror-sync-all
The command @code{wikipedia-mirror} opens a buffer listing all pages stored in @*
the local database, showing each page's title, revision count, last sync @*
time, and watched status. @*

From the mirror browser, you can open a page for online editing (@samp{RET}, @*
@samp{o}), view its local revision history (@samp{h}), synchronize a single page @*
(@samp{s}), or synchronize all watched pages (@samp{S}). @*

